---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Updates — Onyx Labs"
  description="Company updates, product changes, and announcements from Onyx Labs."
>
  <section class="updates-main">
    <div class="container shell">
      <div class="updates-header">
        <div class="content-kicker">Onyx Labs</div>
        <h1 class="content-heading">Updates</h1>
        <p class="content-lede">What we've been building, shipping, and thinking about.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="updates-layout">
        <!-- Sticky date nav -->
        <aside class="updates-sidebar">
          <ul class="updates-nav" id="updatesNav">
            <li><a href="#mar-2025">Mar 2025</a></li>
            <li><a href="#feb-2025">Feb 2025</a></li>
            <li><a href="#jan-2025">Jan 2025</a></li>
            <li><a href="#dec-2024">Dec 2024</a></li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

        <!-- Feed -->
        <div class="updates-feed">

          <article class="update-entry" id="mar-2025">
            <div class="update-date">March 2025</div>
            <h2 class="update-title">AI Governance framework now available as a standalone engagement</h2>
            <div class="update-tags">
              <span class="tag">AI Governance</span>
              <span class="tag">New offering</span>
            </div>
            <div class="update-body">
              <p>
                Our AI Governance framework — previously bundled inside larger consulting engagements — is now
                available as a focused, standalone offering. Teams can adopt it independently without committing
                to a broader partnership.
              </p>
              <p>The framework covers:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Risk classification and model inventory</li>
                <li>Policy templates for model use, data handling, and human oversight</li>
                <li>Review and sign-off workflows for new AI features</li>
                <li>Incident response playbooks</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Engagements typically run four to six weeks and result in a governance package your team owns
                and maintains going forward.
              </p>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="update-entry" id="feb-2025">
            <div class="update-date">February 2025</div>
            <h2 class="update-title">Launched web hosting for AI-native applications</h2>
            <div class="update-tags">
              <span class="tag">Web Hosting</span>
              <span class="tag">Infrastructure</span>
            </div>
            <div class="update-body">
              <p>
                We expanded our services to include managed web hosting, specifically tuned for AI-native
                applications that have variable compute patterns, streaming requirements, and strict latency
                budgets.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Edge-first deployments with global CDN</li>
                <li>Native support for SSE and WebSocket streaming</li>
                <li>Integrated observability for AI request traces</li>
                <li>SLA-backed uptime with on-call support</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This service is available to existing Onyx Labs clients as well as teams seeking hosting
                without a full consulting engagement.
              </p>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="update-entry" id="jan-2025">
            <div class="update-date">January 2025</div>
            <h2 class="update-title">AI Training programs redesigned around role-specific tracks</h2>
            <div class="update-tags">
              <span class="tag">AI Training</span>
              <span class="tag">Curriculum</span>
            </div>
            <div class="update-body">
              <p>
                We overhauled our training curriculum after noticing that mixed-audience workshops produced
                uneven results. The new format splits into three tracks — Product, Engineering, and Leadership
                — each with its own depth, exercises, and outcomes.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Product track:</strong> AI product design, prompt workflows, evaluations</li>
                <li><strong>Engineering track:</strong> Model integration, RAG, evals, observability</li>
                <li><strong>Leadership track:</strong> Risk, policy, build-vs-buy, ROI framing</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Teams can run all three in sequence or pick the track most relevant to them. Each track is
                available as a half-day workshop or a multi-session program.
              </p>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="update-entry" id="dec-2024">
            <div class="update-date">December 2024</div>
            <h2 class="update-title">Onyx Labs founded</h2>
            <div class="update-tags">
              <span class="tag">Company</span>
            </div>
            <div class="update-body">
              <p>
                Onyx Labs launched with a clear mandate: help product companies ship responsible AI
                without sacrificing speed or control. The founding team comes from backgrounds in AI
                engineering, product strategy, and enterprise risk.
              </p>
              <p>
                We started with a single belief — that the teams building AI today need a partner who
                can operate at every layer, from policy to production. That's still what we're here for.
              </p>
            </div>
          </article>

        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    // Highlight active date in sidebar as user scrolls
    (function () {
      const nav = document.getElementById('updatesNav');
      if (!nav) return;
      const links = Array.from(nav.querySelectorAll('a'));
      const entries = links.map(a => document.querySelector(a.getAttribute('href')));

      function onScroll() {
        let current = entries[0];
        for (const entry of entries) {
          if (entry && entry.getBoundingClientRect().top <= 120) current = entry;
        }
        links.forEach(a => a.classList.remove('active'));
        const activeLink = links.find(a => a.getAttribute('href') === '#' + current?.id);
        if (activeLink) activeLink.classList.add('active');
      }

      window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true });
      onScroll();
    })();
  </script>
</BaseLayout>
